                Cooktop repair costs can vary significantly depending on the type of cooktop, the nature of the problem, and the specific parts required for the fix. For minor issues, such as replacing a malfunctioning burner on an electric cooktop, repair costs might range from <b>$50 to $150</b>, including both parts and labor. On the other hand, more complex repairs, like fixing wiring issues or replacing a control board, can cost anywhere from <b>$200 to $500</b>. Gas cooktop repairs tend to be slightly more expensive due to the additional safety measures required. For instance, addressing ignition problems or fixing a gas leak can cost between <b>$100 and $400</b>, depending on the severity of the issue and the repair technician's rates.
              </p>

              <p>
                It's also worth noting that labor costs can vary based on geographic location and the expertise of the technician. In urban areas or regions with a higher cost of living, labor charges may be higher, potentially adding an additional <b>$50 to $100</b> per hour to the repair bill. Emergency or same-day services can also come with a premium, sometimes increasing the overall cost by 20% to 50%. For homeowners considering whether to repair or replace their cooktop, it's important to weigh the repair costs against the price of a new unit, which can range from <b>$300</b> for basic models to over <b>$1,500</b> for high-end cooktops. Regular maintenance and timely repairs can often extend the lifespan of a cooktop, making the investment in repairs a cost-effective option in the long run.
              </p>
